w
[Main Street]
North and south of the road, twin towers guard the road to the palace.  A
huge double gate waits to swing shut to protect the Royal Family should the
need arise.  You see at least a dozen alert soldiers from both the Royal
Guard and the Crimson Band.  Overhead, you notice that there is a bridge
between the towers some fifteen feet over the street.
Obvious exits: east, west.
> w
w
[Main Street]
A two story building on the south side of the street seems to have quite a
few Crimson Band and Royal Guard soldiers hanging outside as well as coming
and going.  Just to the east, twin guard towers rise above the buildings.
Obvious exits: east, west.
> w
w
[Main Street]
Beautiful new three story residences here are the rave of the city.  There
three of them along the street, two on the north, one of the south.  Various
scribes and runners are lurking around the entrances to all three of the
buildings, as if they know the inhabitants might need them.   
Obvious exits: east, west.
> w
w
[Main Street]
Just outside the gate of the Palace, most of the traffic here are people
of the court.  Pages, courtiers and nobles alike are scurrying around,
each on their own agenda.  On the south side of the street is a newly
finished building.  The building is a magnificent stone edifice of stately
grace.  Banners from the building flaunt royal blue fields with a tiger's
paw on them.  Two pairs of Royal Guards flank the stone arch that leads to
the interior.  Another two pair stand at the base of the stone steps that
rise to the arch.
Obvious exits: east, west.
> w
w
[Main Street]
You stand before the grand splendor of the new Palace Gates.  The walls
supporting them are taller than they were as well, and flanking towers
stand higher than the walls.  The length of Main Street extends east
all the way to the gate.  
Obvious exits: east.
